00:00:28.760 --> 00:00:34.520
PROFESSOR: OK, well, Mark
Jarzombek is a professor of

00:00:34.520 --> 00:00:36.520
architecture here and has
written this really

00:00:36.520 --> 00:00:38.230
interesting book.

00:00:38.230 --> 00:00:41.360
MARK JARZOMBEK: So if you have
any questions about something

00:00:41.360 --> 00:00:44.660
you don't understand, or you
need to clarify or elaborate,

00:00:44.660 --> 00:00:46.175
just raise your hand
and say so.

00:00:46.175 --> 00:00:48.940
I just sort of picked
some images out.

00:00:48.940 --> 00:00:54.710
First, I'm sure you've seen
the Rogers Building, which

00:00:54.710 --> 00:00:56.040
doesn't exist anymore,
as you know.

00:00:56.040 --> 00:00:58.030
I mean, this building
still exists.

00:00:58.030 --> 00:00:59.890
I'm not sure what happened
to the store.

00:00:59.890 --> 00:01:01.225
Did they go bankrupt?

00:01:01.225 --> 00:01:03.200
[INAUDIBLE].

00:01:03.200 --> 00:01:06.390
But this was torn down.

00:01:06.390 --> 00:01:10.090
But what I point out in my book
is that if we look at

00:01:10.090 --> 00:01:15.720
this and we go, well, it's
1860s, and you want to make a

00:01:15.720 --> 00:01:21.850
building for an institute that
does sciences, what do you do?

00:01:21.850 --> 00:01:24.650
I mean, what should
it look like?

00:01:24.650 --> 00:01:27.670
And so we may look at this and
say, well, it's sort of a

00:01:27.670 --> 00:01:29.740
building like any
other building.

00:01:29.740 --> 00:01:33.340
But it's sort of a bit of a
problem because that type of a

00:01:33.340 --> 00:01:36.000
building didn't really exist.

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:39.470
So the architect did something
that was pretty clever, but

00:01:39.470 --> 00:01:44.230
also says something about
the world view.

00:01:44.230 --> 00:01:48.070
Basically the building is
modeled a little bit on the

00:01:48.070 --> 00:01:48.880
Apsley House.

00:01:48.880 --> 00:01:52.520
And basically is a gentleman's
residence.

00:01:52.520 --> 00:01:54.330
So you want to make
a building.

00:01:54.330 --> 00:01:57.440
You want to make scientist and
technology guys, miners

00:01:57.440 --> 00:02:01.530
walking around in their big
boots, you want to tell them

00:02:01.530 --> 00:02:03.740
that they're basically not just
doing technology, but

00:02:03.740 --> 00:02:04.810
basically they're gentlemen.

00:02:04.810 --> 00:02:07.080
So the students that are coming
in here are meant to be

00:02:07.080 --> 00:02:11.070
raised at a level of gentlemen
in the 19th

00:02:11.070 --> 00:02:13.970
century sense of that.

00:02:13.970 --> 00:02:15.630
They're sort of cultural
holders of a

00:02:15.630 --> 00:02:16.930
type of cultural thing.

00:02:16.930 --> 00:02:20.270
They're not just wandering
around, shuffling around with

00:02:20.270 --> 00:02:24.060
slide rulers in their hand
thinking about science.

00:02:24.060 --> 00:02:27.720
They have a certain
status in society.

00:02:27.720 --> 00:02:31.370
So basically this is a
gentleman's residence that is,

00:02:31.370 --> 00:02:34.700
then, sort of designed on the
inside to be a school.

00:02:34.700 --> 00:02:38.780
So this says something about the
transition of science into

00:02:38.780 --> 00:02:40.360
legitimacy.

00:02:40.360 --> 00:02:45.310
And the type of premodern notion
signs, where science

00:02:45.310 --> 00:02:50.820
was still associated with sort
of a gentlemanly class and

00:02:50.820 --> 00:02:53.160
gentlemanly behavior.

00:02:53.160 --> 00:02:59.740
So that is MIT's first
source of claim,

00:02:59.740 --> 00:03:01.110
which was very expected.

00:03:01.110 --> 00:03:04.250
Perhaps you think of the
mid-19th century worldview.

00:03:04.250 --> 00:03:09.560
Of course, what happens is that
MIT grows gangbusters and

00:03:09.560 --> 00:03:13.590
starts to spread out
in every direction.

00:03:13.590 --> 00:03:16.930
So there you see the
Rogers Building.

00:03:16.930 --> 00:03:19.690
And then there's their Walker
building, which is a chemistry

00:03:19.690 --> 00:03:20.780
building, a beautiful
building.

00:03:20.780 --> 00:03:23.820
One of the first buildings
specifically designed for

00:03:23.820 --> 00:03:25.710
chemical fumes and so forth.

00:03:25.710 --> 00:03:30.030
And then here and there and
right and left, the campus

00:03:30.030 --> 00:03:35.630
expands around Copley Square
into warehouses and into sheds

00:03:35.630 --> 00:03:37.570
and other things.

00:03:37.570 --> 00:03:40.590
The Lowell Laboratory
gets built here.

00:03:40.590 --> 00:03:42.560
But as you can see, after
a while, it's

00:03:42.560 --> 00:03:43.810
something like 20 buildings.

00:03:46.420 --> 00:03:51.730
The face was that not only is
the buildings all over around

00:03:51.730 --> 00:03:52.880
Copley Square--

00:03:52.880 --> 00:03:55.036
which is difficult if you want
to go from class to class in

00:03:55.036 --> 00:03:56.850
the middle of a snowstorm--

00:03:56.850 --> 00:04:00.770
but also, science was
changing, too.

00:04:00.770 --> 00:04:03.530
So the professors were
complaining they needed dust

00:04:03.530 --> 00:04:05.690
free environments to
do certain things.

00:04:05.690 --> 00:04:10.290
They needed laboratories that
won't shake every time the

00:04:10.290 --> 00:04:12.250
beer truck rumbles by.

00:04:12.250 --> 00:04:15.810
So if you're in the middle of
a city, 19th century cities

00:04:15.810 --> 00:04:20.630
where unbelievably stinky, fumy
places filled with black

00:04:20.630 --> 00:04:23.040
soot from chimneys.

00:04:23.040 --> 00:04:28.000
I mean, today clean air law has
done a lot to our cities.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:32.120
But you've got to imagine, into
the winter the heavy odor

00:04:32.120 --> 00:04:35.650
and cloud of soot making
everything sort of black.

00:04:35.650 --> 00:04:38.210
And so if you do any experiments
that require

00:04:38.210 --> 00:04:39.830
special atmospheres,
and this and that.

00:04:39.830 --> 00:04:43.270
So the professors were
complaining about

00:04:43.270 --> 00:04:44.130
being in the city.

00:04:44.130 --> 00:04:46.070
They wanted to be away from the
city, away from the noise,

00:04:46.070 --> 00:04:48.170
and the pollution, and
the sounds, and all

00:04:48.170 --> 00:04:49.880
that type of stuff.

00:04:49.880 --> 00:04:52.770
So this was sort of one
of the problems

00:04:52.770 --> 00:04:55.130
that the faculty faced.

00:04:55.130 --> 00:04:56.960
And one of the reasons
that spread along

00:04:56.960 --> 00:05:01.670
the desire to move.

00:05:01.670 --> 00:05:07.220
So then the question was,
well, what you do?

00:05:07.220 --> 00:05:10.070
So you need a bigger building.

00:05:10.070 --> 00:05:14.840
So the model for this was
actually in Europe, mainly in

00:05:14.840 --> 00:05:19.210
Germany, and then Switzerland.

00:05:19.210 --> 00:05:23.490
So the ETH was created, you see,
almost at the same time,

00:05:23.490 --> 00:05:24.450
but designed a little
bit earlier.

00:05:24.450 --> 00:05:26.640
Gigantic building.

00:05:26.640 --> 00:05:33.660
So here, I mean, this makes MIT
look, I mean, literally,

00:05:33.660 --> 00:05:36.710
like a joke compared to what
the Swiss investment in

00:05:36.710 --> 00:05:39.010
technology was at that time.

00:05:39.010 --> 00:05:44.680
Huge building, massive amount of
laboratories, huge library.

00:05:44.680 --> 00:05:49.590
I mean, this was an institution
of gigantic scale.

00:05:49.590 --> 00:05:54.300
So here we have the United
States trying to create some

00:05:54.300 --> 00:05:57.070
enthusiasm for the independence
of science and

00:05:57.070 --> 00:06:02.000
learning and technology as
a material, and basically

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:06.370
adopting, initially at least,
not the German model, which

00:06:06.370 --> 00:06:08.890
was that this is a massive
institution supported by the

00:06:08.890 --> 00:06:10.780
state government.

00:06:10.780 --> 00:06:11.850
And it still is.

00:06:11.850 --> 00:06:14.270
The ETH is financed and
supported by the state

00:06:14.270 --> 00:06:14.590
government.

00:06:14.590 --> 00:06:16.920
If you're a professor there,
the prime minister has to,

00:06:16.920 --> 00:06:18.985
ultimately, accept your
tenure proposal, not

00:06:18.985 --> 00:06:22.140
the university president.

00:06:22.140 --> 00:06:26.660
Whereas MIT adopted sort of the
English gentleman model.

00:06:26.660 --> 00:06:31.070
Which is very low key,
different worldview.

00:06:31.070 --> 00:06:35.300
Ultimately, of course,
this wins out.

00:06:35.300 --> 00:06:38.080
But the transition
is what's sort of

00:06:38.080 --> 00:06:40.160
interesting about this.

00:06:40.160 --> 00:06:43.790
So Robert Ware, who's founded
the School of

00:06:43.790 --> 00:06:45.850
Architecture here.

00:06:45.850 --> 00:06:47.730
"The first principle of
architecture is truthfulness,

00:06:47.730 --> 00:06:49.970
good sense, perspicuity.

00:06:49.970 --> 00:06:52.670
Considerations of method,
order, form, clearness,

00:06:52.670 --> 00:06:55.280
precision, sobriety, are what
make a good working style,

00:06:55.280 --> 00:06:57.600
both in writing and in
building." So in other words,

00:06:57.600 --> 00:07:00.460
he's describing a building.

00:07:00.460 --> 00:07:02.560
But in reality, he's also
describing what it means to be

00:07:02.560 --> 00:07:03.770
a gentleman.

00:07:03.770 --> 00:07:07.130
A gentleman is truthful,
and good, and has great

00:07:07.130 --> 00:07:08.510
perspicuity.

00:07:08.510 --> 00:07:11.300
Order, form, clearness,
precision, sobriety--

00:07:11.300 --> 00:07:14.120
this is what you tell
a young man to be.

00:07:14.120 --> 00:07:17.770
So in some sense, we can sort
of read through some of the

00:07:17.770 --> 00:07:22.620
architectural mandate a type of
relationship to, in fact,

00:07:22.620 --> 00:07:25.720
MIT's mandate, which was
what kind of men--

00:07:25.720 --> 00:07:27.780
because it was all men in those
days-- what kind of man

00:07:27.780 --> 00:07:29.030
are we trying to shape here?

00:07:32.010 --> 00:07:34.630
But then, of course,
the world changed.

00:07:34.630 --> 00:07:44.540
So in 1863, we have the four
categories, of which basically

00:07:44.540 --> 00:07:48.670
fine arts and architecture
is the only one

00:07:48.670 --> 00:07:50.820
that survives as such.

00:07:50.820 --> 00:07:54.130
Course four is the only one that
sort of keeps us going.

00:07:54.130 --> 00:07:58.060
But you see in 1873 all
of a sudden we have

00:07:58.060 --> 00:07:59.840
different type of world.

00:07:59.840 --> 00:08:04.090
It's astonishing how in
basically 10 years, MIT's

00:08:04.090 --> 00:08:05.860
mindset has changed.

00:08:05.860 --> 00:08:08.650
So before, we had agriculture.

00:08:08.650 --> 00:08:11.700
Farmer Joe wanted to figure
out how to lay

00:08:11.700 --> 00:08:13.190
out a field, right?

00:08:13.190 --> 00:08:16.120
Well, agriculture, we don't
do agriculture anymore.

00:08:16.120 --> 00:08:19.570
I mean, go out in
Kansas for that.

00:08:19.570 --> 00:08:21.860
At the top of the heap is
civil engineering now.

00:08:21.860 --> 00:08:25.850
So you can sort of see, you go
from an institution that is

00:08:25.850 --> 00:08:28.650
really sort of about
agriculture, geology,

00:08:28.650 --> 00:08:34.169
chemistry, very sort
of oddly primitive.

00:08:34.169 --> 00:08:34.900
I don't know, you know?

00:08:34.900 --> 00:08:39.270
It's sort of an institution
where we could sort of see

00:08:39.270 --> 00:08:41.390
modernity being formed.

00:08:41.390 --> 00:08:44.000
So civil engineering, mechanical
engineering,

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:49.500
geology, architecture
stays, chemistry.

00:08:49.500 --> 00:08:53.840
So here, history, geology, and
chemistry were all one

00:08:53.840 --> 00:08:54.630
department.

00:08:54.630 --> 00:08:57.010
Maybe it's sort of a little
bit hard to imagine that.

00:08:57.010 --> 00:08:59.650
You know, natural history,
geology, and chemistry all

00:08:59.650 --> 00:09:02.270
being sort of one thing.

00:09:02.270 --> 00:09:06.250
But we sort of imagine that
during this time, there was

00:09:06.250 --> 00:09:12.730
still debate about, let's
say, for example,

00:09:12.730 --> 00:09:14.890
what do you call these?

00:09:14.890 --> 00:09:16.390
Dinosaur bones in the sand.

00:09:16.390 --> 00:09:17.420
What do you call them?

00:09:17.420 --> 00:09:17.920
Fossils.

00:09:17.920 --> 00:09:18.260
AUDIENCE: Fossils.

00:09:18.260 --> 00:09:18.910
MARK JARZOMBEK: Right, right.

00:09:18.910 --> 00:09:19.860
You don't know, OK.

00:09:19.860 --> 00:09:23.060
So up until 1820, 1830, they
all said that God put the

00:09:23.060 --> 00:09:25.680
fossils there because they were
the mistakes that when he

00:09:25.680 --> 00:09:27.930
made heaven and earth, he
made a few mistakes.

00:09:27.930 --> 00:09:31.980
So he put them in the ground
so no one would see them.

00:09:31.980 --> 00:09:33.550
And this was a current theory.

00:09:33.550 --> 00:09:35.940
And people thought this
was sort of it.

00:09:35.940 --> 00:09:40.350
So geology was sort of having to
do with divinity, in a way.

00:09:40.350 --> 00:09:41.840
Because when you started
digging, you encounter fossil.

00:09:41.840 --> 00:09:43.290
It's like, there's
God's mistake.

00:09:43.290 --> 00:09:44.370
And it's like, what
do you do with it?

00:09:44.370 --> 00:09:46.370
I mean, he should cover it up.

00:09:46.370 --> 00:09:50.000
So geology, chemistry,
everything, these ideas were

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:51.300
still floating around.

00:09:51.300 --> 00:09:52.490
I mean, not so much here.

00:09:52.490 --> 00:09:57.600
But you can sort of see geology
wasn't what this is.

00:09:57.600 --> 00:09:59.060
And you can see where
geology is going.

00:09:59.060 --> 00:10:03.630
It goes from just looking
at stones to mining.

00:10:03.630 --> 00:10:08.270
Which we can sort of see by the
time we get to 1900 a much

00:10:08.270 --> 00:10:12.170
more sort of precise focus of
how the sciences sort of

00:10:12.170 --> 00:10:14.410
operate in the real world now.

00:10:14.410 --> 00:10:16.920
Here this is sort of
all very abstract.

00:10:16.920 --> 00:10:21.640
Here we see the emergence of
whole new genres of reality.

00:10:21.640 --> 00:10:24.110
We have a philosophy
department.

00:10:24.110 --> 00:10:27.570
Philosophy disappears and then,
in a funny way, sort of

00:10:27.570 --> 00:10:30.770
comes back in the
20th century.

00:10:30.770 --> 00:10:35.110
So philosophy is still the
holdover of the idea that you

00:10:35.110 --> 00:10:36.590
should know something
about the world in a

00:10:36.590 --> 00:10:38.190
philosophical way.

00:10:38.190 --> 00:10:40.430
So by 1873, we see the
emergence of the

00:10:40.430 --> 00:10:45.220
professionalization of the
sciences, which means

00:10:45.220 --> 00:10:48.910
professional journals,
publications.

00:10:48.910 --> 00:10:51.900
And think, all the things we
assume completely normal today

00:10:51.900 --> 00:10:54.500
just really didn't exist,
actually, until really into

00:10:54.500 --> 00:10:58.980
the 1880s and 1890s, sort of
journal publications and peer

00:10:58.980 --> 00:11:03.020
reviewed publications, and
so forth like that.

00:11:03.020 --> 00:11:08.950
So then by 1900, we see we
have now 13 departments.

00:11:08.950 --> 00:11:11.060
So it's sort of growing
exponentially.

00:11:11.060 --> 00:11:12.510
And it has continued to grow.

00:11:12.510 --> 00:11:15.060
We got, I don't know,
23 AB now.

00:11:15.060 --> 00:11:19.760
I mean, we're at least
in the mid '20s.

00:11:19.760 --> 00:11:21.100
And we see new things.

00:11:24.450 --> 00:11:28.320
America's just had the
Spanish American War.

00:11:28.320 --> 00:11:31.670
Naval ships for the Defense
Department are important.

00:11:31.670 --> 00:11:33.170
So we have a Naval architecture
thing.

00:11:35.700 --> 00:11:39.250
The cities in the turn of the
century were really terrible,

00:11:39.250 --> 00:11:41.580
complicated, messy places.

00:11:41.580 --> 00:11:43.080
The streets were not paved.

00:11:43.080 --> 00:11:44.930
There were sewage problems,
and so forth, and so on.

00:11:44.930 --> 00:11:48.810
So sanitary engineering comes
into play along with sort of

00:11:48.810 --> 00:11:50.600
the conventional type thing.

00:11:50.600 --> 00:11:55.200
So we have new departments and
new programs being developed.

00:11:55.200 --> 00:11:57.810
But the point is, in some sense,
what we get here is

00:11:57.810 --> 00:12:02.880
really the modern notion of
science that we just assume is

00:12:02.880 --> 00:12:03.610
completely normal.

00:12:03.610 --> 00:12:07.630
We see it literally happening,
if you will, decade by decade,

00:12:07.630 --> 00:12:10.600
rapidly changing into the
professional world that we

00:12:10.600 --> 00:12:11.740
have today.

00:12:11.740 --> 00:12:15.920
So the model of a gentleman's
villa, it is

00:12:15.920 --> 00:12:19.550
just clearly not working.

00:12:19.550 --> 00:12:23.600
But of course, the building
remained to be functional for

00:12:23.600 --> 00:12:25.410
a long time.

00:12:25.410 --> 00:12:27.910
So the first attempt to, in some
sense, modernize MIT's

00:12:27.910 --> 00:12:29.600
look was the Walker building.

00:12:29.600 --> 00:12:31.750
Here's the Rogers Building
next to it.

00:12:31.750 --> 00:12:33.240
And at first you go, well,
it doesn't look

00:12:33.240 --> 00:12:34.760
all that much different.

00:12:34.760 --> 00:12:36.560
But it was designed with
these chimneys.

00:12:36.560 --> 00:12:40.200
You see the air vent chimneys on
the exterior facade so that

00:12:40.200 --> 00:12:43.700
the chemistry laboratories would
have these vents going

00:12:43.700 --> 00:12:45.940
up to vent the fumes.

00:12:45.940 --> 00:12:48.910
So instead of hiding the
chimneys, the chimneys become,

00:12:48.910 --> 00:12:51.860
in fact, part of the
whole architecture.

00:12:51.860 --> 00:12:56.410
And basically it's sort of the
first real attempt to make a

00:12:56.410 --> 00:12:58.760
laboratory building at
a monumental scale.

00:12:58.760 --> 00:13:00.550
This is in Copley Square,
right across

00:13:00.550 --> 00:13:01.840
from Trinity Church.

00:13:01.840 --> 00:13:06.610
This is one of the best real
state areas in the city.

00:13:06.610 --> 00:13:09.770
And to put a chemistry lab
there, I mean, it's like, oh,

00:13:09.770 --> 00:13:11.340
you got to be kidding
me, right?

00:13:11.340 --> 00:13:17.570
So it shows the capacity to sort
of start to think of what

00:13:17.570 --> 00:13:19.890
a science building is
at an urban scale.

00:13:19.890 --> 00:13:21.820
But still, it's a relatively
small building.

00:13:28.540 --> 00:13:32.150
They were living in these
type of warehouses.

00:13:32.150 --> 00:13:33.880
This was the architecture
building

00:13:33.880 --> 00:13:35.630
and engineering building.

00:13:35.630 --> 00:13:37.800
Which were useful, because you
could much around in there.

00:13:37.800 --> 00:13:42.320
And there was no damage
done, really, if you

00:13:42.320 --> 00:13:45.410
banged in to something.

00:13:45.410 --> 00:13:46.560
They made some of these
experiments.

00:13:46.560 --> 00:13:50.580
They made the lower laboratory
down here, which at the time

00:13:50.580 --> 00:13:53.980
would have been the most
advanced laboratory for

00:13:53.980 --> 00:13:55.640
electrical engineering.

00:13:55.640 --> 00:13:57.310
They only used it
for a few years.

00:13:59.950 --> 00:14:02.220
The building contractor was
a guy called Gilbreth.

00:14:02.220 --> 00:14:04.670
Everybody seen Cheaper
By The Dozen?

00:14:04.670 --> 00:14:09.000
Well, anyway, he's the one who
built the building using new

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:09.530
techniques.

00:14:09.530 --> 00:14:10.950
Because he was famous.

00:14:10.950 --> 00:14:13.260
You know what he
was famous for?

00:14:13.260 --> 00:14:15.210
The guy, Gilbreth?

00:14:15.210 --> 00:14:21.220
Well, he was interested in
making labor less expensive.

00:14:21.220 --> 00:14:24.270
So the ways you do that is you
study, let's say, you take a

00:14:24.270 --> 00:14:25.480
bricklayer.

00:14:25.480 --> 00:14:27.070
And the bricklayer's got
to go get a brick.

00:14:27.070 --> 00:14:29.570
And then he's got to bring
the brick down.

00:14:29.570 --> 00:14:31.060
And then he's got to
put a brick in.

00:14:31.060 --> 00:14:31.810
Then he's hungry.

00:14:31.810 --> 00:14:33.716
They he puts the chewing
gum in his mouth.

00:14:33.716 --> 00:14:35.610
And he slathers something
[INAUDIBLE].

00:14:35.610 --> 00:14:38.010
Well, he figured out that
takes a lot of time.

00:14:38.010 --> 00:14:40.390
So you have the dolly.

00:14:40.390 --> 00:14:41.730
And the dolly will
bring the brick.

00:14:41.730 --> 00:14:42.870
One guy gives the brick.

00:14:42.870 --> 00:14:43.940
The other guy puts it down.

00:14:43.940 --> 00:14:44.920
The other guy slathers it.

00:14:44.920 --> 00:14:47.550
So your job is just to take
the brick and put it down.

00:14:47.550 --> 00:14:48.450
Take the brick, put it down.

00:14:48.450 --> 00:14:49.230
Take the brick, put it down.

00:14:49.230 --> 00:14:49.870
Take the brick.

00:14:49.870 --> 00:14:52.330
And the next guy's job is to
go-- kuh-chunk, kuh-chunk,

00:14:52.330 --> 00:14:54.690
kuh-chunk, kuh-chunk, kuh-chunk,
kuh-chunk.

00:14:54.690 --> 00:14:56.790
And you can build buildings a
lot faster if you do this

00:14:56.790 --> 00:14:58.260
time-saving thing.

00:14:58.260 --> 00:15:01.260
He was the inventor--

00:15:01.260 --> 00:15:03.190
or not the inventor but one
of the great champions of

00:15:03.190 --> 00:15:05.390
time-saving labor.

00:15:05.390 --> 00:15:08.330
Ford Motor works would put it
into mass production window to

00:15:08.330 --> 00:15:10.290
make a Model T Ford.

00:15:10.290 --> 00:15:12.940
So this was sort of advanced
technology at the

00:15:12.940 --> 00:15:16.250
time, if you will.

00:15:16.250 --> 00:15:18.750
And of course, has debatable
effects.

00:15:18.750 --> 00:15:20.910
But anyway.

00:15:20.910 --> 00:15:24.270
So anyway, there he is, Mr.
Gilbreth, with his cheaper by

00:15:24.270 --> 00:15:25.890
the dozen family.

00:15:25.890 --> 00:15:26.940
And so they hired him.

00:15:26.940 --> 00:15:31.800
In other words, they brought in
a new type of engineer to

00:15:31.800 --> 00:15:33.185
experiment with a new
type of building.

00:15:35.840 --> 00:15:40.470
And so it shows MIT's
search for the

00:15:40.470 --> 00:15:42.930
avant-garde of the time.

00:15:42.930 --> 00:15:45.030
So then you compare,
of course, that

00:15:45.030 --> 00:15:46.290
there's MIT's building.

00:15:46.290 --> 00:15:49.290
And this is another building
from 1861.

00:15:49.290 --> 00:15:51.760
The Opera by Charles
Garnier in Paris.

00:15:51.760 --> 00:15:53.140
I don't know if you've
ever seen it.

00:15:53.140 --> 00:15:54.670
But if you go to Paris,
you should see it.

00:15:54.670 --> 00:15:55.350
It's certainly one of the great

00:15:55.350 --> 00:15:56.510
buildings of the 19th century.

00:15:56.510 --> 00:15:58.220
I mean, [? vastly, ?] hugely

00:15:58.220 --> 00:16:02.130
beautiful, extravagant building.

00:16:02.130 --> 00:16:04.790
So once again, in Europe,
they were making

00:16:04.790 --> 00:16:07.320
these gigantic things.

00:16:07.320 --> 00:16:10.990
Whereas at MIT and Boston, there
were still small little

00:16:10.990 --> 00:16:14.940
building after small
little building.

00:16:14.940 --> 00:16:18.450
But they this world, which
is sort of the Beaux-Arts

00:16:18.450 --> 00:16:23.410
architecture here is sort of a
European development of how to

00:16:23.410 --> 00:16:25.840
make these buildings work within
the city, and so forth.

00:16:25.840 --> 00:16:27.850
Wasn't really in the
United States yet.

00:16:27.850 --> 00:16:32.290
And I'd say its building styles
were still English

00:16:32.290 --> 00:16:37.430
driven, still relatively small
scale, still relatively modest

00:16:37.430 --> 00:16:41.870
in their desire in terms
of spacial expression.

00:16:41.870 --> 00:16:46.920
So around the world, you were
having these huge buildings

00:16:46.920 --> 00:16:49.220
being built.

00:16:49.220 --> 00:16:51.930
And so here we are in Japan.

00:16:56.130 --> 00:16:56.890
Here's Cairo.

00:16:56.890 --> 00:16:59.720
I have to show you this because
this is the old

00:16:59.720 --> 00:17:00.890
building from the
medieval period.

00:17:00.890 --> 00:17:05.990
And then they built this
gigantic mosque here in 1910.

00:17:05.990 --> 00:17:09.540
And the Cairo National Museum of
1900, which is in the news

00:17:09.540 --> 00:17:11.160
a little bit today.

00:17:11.160 --> 00:17:15.180
So Boston around 1900 would
have looked like a real

00:17:15.180 --> 00:17:20.849
gritty, brick, working
class place.

00:17:20.849 --> 00:17:24.569
Very few prestigious buildings,
nothing really

00:17:24.569 --> 00:17:26.720
grand about the place at all.

00:17:26.720 --> 00:17:29.700
You had the Back Bay that
had been laid out.

00:17:29.700 --> 00:17:32.210
And you had some fine
residential quarters.

00:17:32.210 --> 00:17:35.770
But you really didn't have
high architecture, any

00:17:35.770 --> 00:17:39.500
examples of high architecture
at all compared to almost

00:17:39.500 --> 00:17:41.850
everywhere else around
the world.

00:17:41.850 --> 00:17:47.790
Well, in 1893, they brought in
this French architect, a guy

00:17:47.790 --> 00:17:53.320
called Despradelle, to teach in
the school of architecture.

00:17:53.320 --> 00:17:56.730
And he sort of changed
everything because he brought

00:17:56.730 --> 00:18:02.510
this much grander, much more
imposing sort of tradition of

00:18:02.510 --> 00:18:04.870
sort of architectural
world that was in

00:18:04.870 --> 00:18:06.600
Europe at the time.

00:18:06.600 --> 00:18:09.030
And it was sort of a risk.

00:18:09.030 --> 00:18:10.390
And so they bought this guy.

00:18:10.390 --> 00:18:12.420
As you can see, he's sort
of a strange character.

00:18:12.420 --> 00:18:15.330
The students sort
of loved him.

00:18:15.330 --> 00:18:20.510
He was very quirky much beloved
by the students.

00:18:20.510 --> 00:18:23.220
We taught them how to make these
absolutely drop dead

00:18:23.220 --> 00:18:25.750
gorgeous drawings, some of
which are in the museum.

00:18:25.750 --> 00:18:29.680
Hopefully we can, one
day, exhibit them.

00:18:29.680 --> 00:18:32.980
This drawing, which was
gigantic, some 12 feet high or

00:18:32.980 --> 00:18:36.070
something, was for a building,
of course,

00:18:36.070 --> 00:18:36.710
that was never built.

00:18:36.710 --> 00:18:39.350
I mean, it was impossible
to build at the time.

00:18:39.350 --> 00:18:41.980
Some huge, huge, huge, huge
monument sort of celebrating

00:18:41.980 --> 00:18:44.860
the Americas called the
"Beacon of Progress."

00:18:44.860 --> 00:18:49.070
So actually it looks a little
old fashioned, because it was,

00:18:49.070 --> 00:18:50.440
like, not a modern building.

00:18:50.440 --> 00:18:51.770
But it would have been
a really very

00:18:51.770 --> 00:18:54.060
early use of concrete.

00:18:54.060 --> 00:18:57.090
It was actually a very
interesting type of edifice.

00:18:57.090 --> 00:18:59.920
And so we have to see it as much
more progressive than we

00:18:59.920 --> 00:19:02.360
today might see things.

00:19:06.410 --> 00:19:09.670
And then he went around and
bought drawings for the

00:19:09.670 --> 00:19:11.020
students to learn.

00:19:11.020 --> 00:19:13.210
So this is another one of the
leading architects of the

00:19:13.210 --> 00:19:15.306
time, a guy called
Viollet-le-Duc.

00:19:15.306 --> 00:19:18.930
And he and Ware basically
brought all these drawings

00:19:18.930 --> 00:19:23.580
from Europe for the architects
to look at to teach them.

00:19:23.580 --> 00:19:27.990
So we have, of course, in the
process, then, drawing

00:19:27.990 --> 00:19:31.370
capitals and things like that
for presentation drawing.

00:19:31.370 --> 00:19:34.740
So all of a sudden, the
principle of architecture,

00:19:34.740 --> 00:19:39.840
prestige, quality buildings
sort of comes into play.

00:19:39.840 --> 00:19:42.240
And these are just drawings
from the archives made by

00:19:42.240 --> 00:19:46.590
students here at the turn
of the century.

00:19:46.590 --> 00:19:52.310
So the point is that basically
he changes the architectural

00:19:52.310 --> 00:19:57.270
culture that's taught here
from just basically more

00:19:57.270 --> 00:20:01.260
pragmatic architectural
buildings to be a type of

00:20:01.260 --> 00:20:04.790
culture that really speaks
to high-end architectural

00:20:04.790 --> 00:20:05.330
production.

00:20:05.330 --> 00:20:07.120
And MIT is really the
first place in the

00:20:07.120 --> 00:20:09.210
country which does that.

00:20:09.210 --> 00:20:12.400
Now that means you and I will
look at this, and [INAUDIBLE]

00:20:12.400 --> 00:20:14.050
all sort of old fashioned.

00:20:14.050 --> 00:20:15.610
We look at this and go, oh,
this is the stuff that

00:20:15.610 --> 00:20:17.330
modernism sort of got rid of.

00:20:17.330 --> 00:20:21.010
But this would be a
bit of a mistake--

00:20:21.010 --> 00:20:26.140
this is a synagogue
that was planned--

00:20:26.140 --> 00:20:31.160
largely because 1900 and that
era was an interesting moment

00:20:31.160 --> 00:20:32.020
in history.

00:20:32.020 --> 00:20:34.260
There was the Spanish
American War.

00:20:34.260 --> 00:20:39.430
And the two sort of, I
guess, events was the

00:20:39.430 --> 00:20:40.635
market crash of 1893.

00:20:40.635 --> 00:20:43.430
1893 was the first stock market
crash in the United

00:20:43.430 --> 00:20:45.020
States, the first great one.

00:20:45.020 --> 00:20:46.860
It's like we never learn.

00:20:46.860 --> 00:20:50.260
It was another big bank
financial scandal of too many

00:20:50.260 --> 00:20:51.450
people buying too much land.

00:20:51.450 --> 00:20:53.220
And then all of a sudden,
it went belly up.

00:20:53.220 --> 00:20:56.350
It was like, duh.

00:20:56.350 --> 00:21:00.530
So anyway, and basically
everybody was out of a job.

00:21:03.050 --> 00:21:05.280
I mean, probably about 10 times
worse than what we have

00:21:05.280 --> 00:21:07.150
today, what we just recently
experienced.

00:21:07.150 --> 00:21:10.090
And probably not quite as
bad as the crash of '29.

00:21:10.090 --> 00:21:12.560
But a significant shock
to the system.

00:21:12.560 --> 00:21:17.580
And after that, the United
States' warehouses were filled

00:21:17.580 --> 00:21:19.960
with stuff that no
one could buy.

00:21:19.960 --> 00:21:21.830
So what they did was they
made it very cheap.

00:21:21.830 --> 00:21:23.270
And they shipped it
around the world.

00:21:23.270 --> 00:21:26.830
And basically the United States,
afterward from 1893,

00:21:26.830 --> 00:21:29.410
basically became an
international supplier of

00:21:29.410 --> 00:21:31.290
things, in particular steel.

00:21:31.290 --> 00:21:36.360
So it discovered international
markets after 1893.

00:21:36.360 --> 00:21:38.980
Then came the Spanish American
War, where America now was a

00:21:38.980 --> 00:21:41.570
quasi-colonial imperial power.

00:21:41.570 --> 00:21:48.270
So by 1900, the United States
had established itself as a

00:21:48.270 --> 00:21:52.350
network, global, expanding
trade world.

00:21:52.350 --> 00:21:56.080
And it wanted to market itself
in particular ways.

00:21:56.080 --> 00:22:00.970
Well, what you could market,
of course, is architecture.

00:22:00.970 --> 00:22:04.980
So MIT knows by teaching its
students how to make these big

00:22:04.980 --> 00:22:08.660
and huge and grand buildings,
whilst preparing them for big

00:22:08.660 --> 00:22:10.550
time commissions around
the world.

00:22:10.550 --> 00:22:12.130
And it's not just these
commissions.

00:22:12.130 --> 00:22:16.000
But it was the steel that came
from the steel factories.

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:17.250
It was the parts that
came from the

00:22:17.250 --> 00:22:18.710
American parts factories.

00:22:18.710 --> 00:22:21.090
It was the labor and the
contractors that came from the

00:22:21.090 --> 00:22:21.910
labor contractor.

00:22:21.910 --> 00:22:24.890
So this was all originally
controlled by the French,

00:22:24.890 --> 00:22:27.360
largely, who built their
buildings as export

00:22:27.360 --> 00:22:27.850
commodities.

00:22:27.850 --> 00:22:31.140
Now MIT's Department of
Architecture really was sort

00:22:31.140 --> 00:22:35.010
of at the cusp of basically
producing architecture as an

00:22:35.010 --> 00:22:36.190
export commodity.

00:22:36.190 --> 00:22:41.150
So it's not just that this
Beaux-Arts architecture, as we

00:22:41.150 --> 00:22:44.490
call it today, is sort
of frilly and cute.

00:22:44.490 --> 00:22:47.510
It basically was the first
world export commodity.

00:22:47.510 --> 00:22:49.650
Because to make a building,
you need steel, you need

00:22:49.650 --> 00:22:50.540
foundations, you need

00:22:50.540 --> 00:22:52.870
technology, you need engineers.

00:22:52.870 --> 00:22:54.320
At the end, it might look
sort of interesting.

00:22:54.320 --> 00:22:56.320
But it's the whole package.

00:22:56.320 --> 00:22:59.040
So this is why MIT
developed this.

00:22:59.040 --> 00:23:01.220
And meanwhile, Harvard
was looking at this.

00:23:01.220 --> 00:23:07.380
And they said, well, if MIT is
gambling for the Beaux-Arts

00:23:07.380 --> 00:23:11.530
and the principle of world
domination, we think that this

00:23:11.530 --> 00:23:12.600
is sort of not correct.

00:23:12.600 --> 00:23:16.970
And we want architecture to be
humble and appropriate to the

00:23:16.970 --> 00:23:17.960
human scale.

00:23:17.960 --> 00:23:20.570
And so they went into
sort of the

00:23:20.570 --> 00:23:22.100
anti-internationalist phase.

00:23:22.100 --> 00:23:24.880
They went into what's called
the arts and crafts.

00:23:24.880 --> 00:23:28.670
So whereas MIT went into sort
of internationalism,

00:23:28.670 --> 00:23:33.050
Beaux-Arts, huge buildings,
Harvard brought in faculty

00:23:33.050 --> 00:23:35.650
that made little
Gothic things.

00:23:35.650 --> 00:23:41.340
Very beautiful, very sweet,
very elegant.

00:23:41.340 --> 00:23:43.990
William Brigham was one of
the professors there.

00:23:43.990 --> 00:23:45.880
And these are the things
that he made.

00:23:48.820 --> 00:23:54.160
And you compare that with Allen
Ross, who is a graduate

00:23:54.160 --> 00:23:56.800
from here, who went
out and built huge

00:23:56.800 --> 00:23:59.570
buildings like this.

00:23:59.570 --> 00:24:05.780
Or Hood, a graduate from MIT
who went off and did the

00:24:05.780 --> 00:24:06.440
Chicago Tribune.

00:24:06.440 --> 00:24:09.620
He did other buildings, the
Rockefeller Center, designed

00:24:09.620 --> 00:24:12.360
part of the Rockefeller Center,
which were gigantic

00:24:12.360 --> 00:24:14.790
buildings, all about
the progressive

00:24:14.790 --> 00:24:15.740
spirit and so forth.

00:24:15.740 --> 00:24:20.470
So this was the two approaches
that MIT and Harvard had at

00:24:20.470 --> 00:24:22.000
the time in architecture.

00:24:22.000 --> 00:24:27.900
MIT went for big-scale,
urban, huge projects.

00:24:27.900 --> 00:24:30.280
Harvard went for the little
scale, for the domestic, for

00:24:30.280 --> 00:24:32.020
the house, and so forth.

00:24:32.020 --> 00:24:35.240
Eventually MIT would
win that argument.

00:24:35.240 --> 00:24:38.620
I mean, it is a short term or
long term perspective on that.

00:24:38.620 --> 00:24:42.070
And Harvard would eventually
bring in a French architect in

00:24:42.070 --> 00:24:44.230
the first decades of
the 20th century.

00:24:44.230 --> 00:24:48.450
And that was sort of the end
of the arts and crafts.

00:24:48.450 --> 00:24:51.720
And so one of the characters
that sort of comes in is, of

00:24:51.720 --> 00:24:55.390
course, Bosworth, who
is a product of MIT.

00:24:55.390 --> 00:24:57.800
So he, in some sense, is a
student of Despradelle.

00:24:57.800 --> 00:25:01.060
He knows and understands
Despradelle's principle of

00:25:01.060 --> 00:25:07.670
buildings that represent the
big international scale.

00:25:07.670 --> 00:25:11.740
Not buildings that are going to
be humble, and sweet, and

00:25:11.740 --> 00:25:13.830
Gothic, and nostalgic.

00:25:13.830 --> 00:25:18.380
So the project that he designs
for MIT is at that large,

00:25:18.380 --> 00:25:19.310
international scale.

00:25:19.310 --> 00:25:23.590
It's meant to be
big and grand.

00:25:23.590 --> 00:25:28.680
Now he worked for
various people.

00:25:28.680 --> 00:25:36.120
But including a man called
Fish-- who was an AT&amp;T CEO--

00:25:36.120 --> 00:25:40.710
and Ware, and some other people,
and Rockefellers.

00:25:40.710 --> 00:25:43.360
He was sort of like a
gentleman's architect.

00:25:43.360 --> 00:25:44.600
He didn't have a big practice.

00:25:44.600 --> 00:25:45.770
He had a small practice.

00:25:45.770 --> 00:25:49.060
But basically these super rich
people would bring him in to

00:25:49.060 --> 00:25:49.660
design buildings.

00:25:49.660 --> 00:25:50.640
So this is one of the
buildings are

00:25:50.640 --> 00:25:51.760
designed in New York.

00:25:51.760 --> 00:25:55.450
It's literally right next to,
no longer the World Trade

00:25:55.450 --> 00:25:59.230
Center, the towers which you
don't see anymore, which would

00:25:59.230 --> 00:26:00.570
be right there.

00:26:00.570 --> 00:26:04.650
So if any of you know New York,
the Wall Street area,

00:26:04.650 --> 00:26:06.510
you would hopefully know
this building.

00:26:06.510 --> 00:26:11.140
Really a gorgeous building,
strictly neoclassical.

00:26:11.140 --> 00:26:14.410
It has a Doric on the inside,
ionic on the outside.

00:26:14.410 --> 00:26:15.770
But it's a steel building.

00:26:15.770 --> 00:26:17.540
Basically it's a modern steel
building wrapped in

00:26:17.540 --> 00:26:19.790
this sort of casing.

00:26:19.790 --> 00:26:24.920
And the casing is meant to show
the stability of AT&amp;T,

00:26:24.920 --> 00:26:26.880
the magnificence
of it as well.

00:26:26.880 --> 00:26:30.050
So these buildings, which we
may look at as sort of a

00:26:30.050 --> 00:26:34.730
little bit old fashioned were,
at that time, all about the

00:26:34.730 --> 00:26:36.130
bravura of these new

00:26:36.130 --> 00:26:38.110
corporations that were emerging.

00:26:38.110 --> 00:26:40.100
So in particular,
sort of AT&amp;T--

